1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:09,500
Most production problems don't happen in the first minute of a session.

2
00:00:09,800 --> 00:00:12,800
They happen in the seven minutes before it,

3
00:00:13,100 --> 00:00:16,100
when someone forgot to check the microphone battery,

4
00:00:16,400 --> 00:00:19,775
or the slides are still on the wrong laptop,

5
00:00:20,075 --> 00:00:23,825
or nobody confirmed the interpreter booth is on channel two.

6
00:00:24,125 --> 00:00:27,125
The Cue Engine is CueDeck's answer to that.

7
00:00:27,425 --> 00:00:29,675
It watches your session schedule, and

8
00:00:29,975 --> 00:00:32,975
eight minutes before every session's planned start time,

9
00:00:33,275 --> 00:00:37,025
it fires a modal with a tailored pre-cue checklist —

10
00:00:37,325 --> 00:00:39,950
generated by AI, specific to that session.

11
00:00:40,250 --> 00:00:42,875
Let me show you exactly what happens.

12
00:00:43,175 --> 00:00:46,175
A pre-cue is a standard stage management concept.

13
00:00:46,475 --> 00:00:48,725
It's the window of time —

14
00:00:49,025 --> 00:00:52,775
typically between five and ten minutes before a session —

15
00:00:53,075 --> 00:00:55,325
where you run your final checks.

16
00:00:55,625 --> 00:00:57,625
Speaker arrived and miked up?

17
00:00:57,925 --> 00:01:00,550
Slides confirmed and on the opening frame?

18
00:01:00,850 --> 00:01:02,850
AV routing confirmed?

19
00:01:03,150 --> 00:01:05,150
Streaming encoder hot and stable?

20
00:01:05,450 --> 00:01:07,450
Interpretation channels live?

21
00:01:07,750 --> 00:01:10,750
Traditionally this lives on a paper checklist or

22
00:01:11,050 --> 00:01:13,050
in your stage manager's head.

23
00:01:13,350 --> 00:01:15,975
The Cue Engine puts it in CueDeck,

24
00:01:16,275 --> 00:01:18,525
makes it specific to each session,

25
00:01:18,825 --> 00:01:23,325
and makes sure it actually fires at the right moment — automatically.

26
00:01:23,625 --> 00:01:27,375
The engine fires eight minutes before the session's scheduled start.

27
00:01:27,675 --> 00:01:32,175
That gives you time to catch a problem and actually fix it.

28
00:01:32,475 --> 00:01:35,850
Here's what you see when the Cue Engine fires.

29
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:39,525
The modal slides in with an orange accent —

30
00:01:39,825 --> 00:01:43,200
distinct from the red of the Incident Advisor —

31
00:01:43,500 --> 00:01:46,500
because this is a warning, not a crisis.

32
00:01:46,800 --> 00:01:50,550
At the top: the session title, start time, and room.

33
00:01:50,850 --> 00:01:52,850
Below that, the countdown timer.

34
00:01:53,150 --> 00:01:55,775
Right now it shows seven minutes and

35
00:01:56,075 --> 00:01:58,700
fifty-eight seconds, ticking down in real time.

36
00:01:58,1000 --> 00:02:02,750
When you get under two minutes the timer turns red

37
00:02:03,050 --> 00:02:06,425
and starts blinking — a final visual prompt that

38
00:02:06,725 --> 00:02:08,975
you're about to miss your window.

39
00:02:09,275 --> 00:02:11,900
Below the timer is a progress bar.

40
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:14,450
It depletes as time runs out.

41
00:02:14,750 --> 00:02:18,500
You can see at a glance how much of your

42
00:02:18,800 --> 00:02:20,800
pre-cue window you've used.

43
00:02:21,100 --> 00:02:23,350
And here is the part that

44
00:02:23,650 --> 00:02:27,025
makes the Cue Engine more than just a timer.

45
00:02:27,325 --> 00:02:31,075
While the modal is opening, Claude is generating a checklist

46
00:02:31,375 --> 00:02:33,375
specific to this session.

47
00:02:33,675 --> 00:02:36,300
It knows the session title, the room,

48
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:40,725
the start time, and any notes you've attached to the session.

49
00:02:41,025 --> 00:02:44,775
From that, it builds a prioritised list of pre-cue tasks

50
00:02:45,075 --> 00:02:49,950
— not generic ones, but ones appropriate to what this session actually involves.

51
00:02:50,250 --> 00:02:53,250
For a panel discussion with four wireless microphones,

52
00:02:53,550 --> 00:02:58,425
you'll see items about confirming all four mic packs are charged and live.

53
00:02:58,725 --> 00:03:00,975
For a session with Polish and

54
00:03:01,275 --> 00:03:05,400
German interpretation, there'll be a booth check item for both channels.

55
00:03:05,700 --> 00:03:08,325
For a keynote with a streaming feed,

56
00:03:08,625 --> 00:03:11,250
the encoder status check will be there.

57
00:03:11,550 --> 00:03:14,925
Each item has a coloured tag on the right:

58
00:03:15,225 --> 00:03:18,225
CREW items are blue, SYSTEM items are orange,

59
00:03:18,525 --> 00:03:20,525
INTERP items are purple.

60
00:03:20,825 --> 00:03:24,575
At a glance you can see what category each task

61
00:03:24,875 --> 00:03:27,125
falls into and who owns it.

62
00:03:27,425 --> 00:03:31,175
As you confirm each item with your team, click it.

63
00:03:31,475 --> 00:03:33,725
It turns green, strikes through, and

64
00:03:34,025 --> 00:03:36,650
the completion counter at the bottom updates.

65
00:03:36,950 --> 00:03:40,700
If your stage manager is calling in confirmations over comms,

66
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:43,625
you're clicking them off in real time.

67
00:03:43,925 --> 00:03:48,050
When everything is checked, hit CUE READY at the bottom right.

68
00:03:48,350 --> 00:03:50,975
The modal closes, CueDeck logs the confirmation,

69
00:03:51,275 --> 00:03:53,900
and you're cleared to go live when

70
00:03:54,200 --> 00:03:56,450
the session hits its start time.

71
00:03:56,750 --> 00:03:59,000
If you need a moment —

72
00:03:59,300 --> 00:04:02,300
you're in the middle of another conversation —

73
00:04:02,600 --> 00:04:04,600
hit SNOOZE 2 MIN.

74
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:09,400
The modal dismisses and re-fires two minutes later so nothing gets missed.

75
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:12,700
Here's the real value of the Cue Engine:

76
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:17,125
it removes the need to remember to do your pre-cue checks.

77
00:04:17,425 --> 00:04:19,675
On a long conference day —

78
00:04:19,975 --> 00:04:22,600
ten sessions across three rooms, back-to-back panels,

79
00:04:22,900 --> 00:04:25,150
speaker changes every forty-five minutes —

80
00:04:25,450 --> 00:04:29,200
it is very easy to miss the eight-minute window for

81
00:04:29,500 --> 00:04:32,125
a session because you're handling something else.

82
00:04:32,425 --> 00:04:35,800
The engine watches every session's start time simultaneously and

83
00:04:36,100 --> 00:04:39,100
fires the modal when each one is due.

84
00:04:39,400 --> 00:04:41,650
You don't have to set alarms,

85
00:04:41,950 --> 00:04:44,575
you don't have to watch the clock,

86
00:04:44,875 --> 00:04:48,250
you don't have to maintain a separate checklist document.

87
00:04:48,550 --> 00:04:51,175
And because the checklist is AI-generated and

88
00:04:51,475 --> 00:04:53,725
session-specific, it adapts to each cue.

89
00:04:54,025 --> 00:04:57,775
A registration desk walkthrough gets different items than a technical

90
00:04:58,075 --> 00:05:00,075
keynote with a livestream.

91
00:05:00,375 --> 00:05:02,375
That's the Cue Engine.

92
00:05:02,675 --> 00:05:06,425
Eight minutes before every session, a tailored readiness checklist fires

93
00:05:06,725 --> 00:05:10,100
automatically — no setup required, no alarms to set,

94
00:05:10,400 --> 00:05:12,400
no paper lists to maintain.

95
00:05:12,700 --> 00:05:16,075
In the next episode we're covering the third and

96
00:05:16,375 --> 00:05:19,000
final AI agent: the Post-Event Report Generator.

97
00:05:19,300 --> 00:05:23,050
After your event wraps, one click generates a full written

98
00:05:23,350 --> 00:05:25,600
debrief — summary stats, variance table,

99
00:05:25,900 --> 00:05:29,275
incident log, and a narrative written by Claude that

100
00:05:29,575 --> 00:05:32,200
you can send directly to your client.

101
00:05:32,500 --> 00:05:34,500
I'll see you there.
